name: qaap1lp21_01
label: QAAP1LP21_1 Alcohol should be sold at a minimum price of at least 50p per unit.

name: qaap1lp21_02
label: QAAP1LP21_2 All products labels should feature health warnings labels designed by an independent health body.

name: qaap1lp21_03
label: QAAP1LP21_3 The sale of alcohol in shops should be restricted to between 10am and 10pm (as already implemented in Scotland).

name: qaap1lp21_04
label: QAAP1LP21_4 Alcoholic drinks should be taxed in proportion to the amount of alcohol they contain.

name: qaap1lp21_05
label: QAAP1LP21_05 Public health should be considered when applications are made for alcohol outlets

name: qaap1lp21_06
label: QAAP1LP21_06 Stronger measures should be introduced to limit children and young people's exposure to alcohol advertising

name: qaap1lp21_07
label: QAAP1LP21_7 An independent body should be established to regulate alcohol promotion, including product and packaging design.

name: qaap1lp21_08
label: QAAP1LP21_08 Change the legal limit for blood alcohol concentration for drivers to 0mg/100 ml (i.e. zero tolerance for drink-driving).

name: qaap1lp21_09
label: QAAP1LP21_9 All health and social care professionals should be trained to routinely provide advice about alcohol to their clients.

name: qaap1lp21_10
label: QAAP1LP21_10 Everybody who needs support for alcohol problems should be able to access it.

name: qaap1lp21_11
label: QAAP1LP21_11 Require the alcohol industry to publicly disclose business information relevant to its activities (such as sales data, details of lobbying and mark

name: qaap1lp21_12
label: QAAP1LP21_12 All product labels should state the number of calories in the product

name: qaap1lp21_13
label: QAAP1LP21_13 Alcohol products should be less visible in supermarkets and shops (i.e. restrictions on how alcohol is displayed)

name: qaap1lp21_14
label: QAAP1LP21_14 High strength drinks should be taxed at a higher rate than lower strength drinks.

name: qaap1lp21_15
label: QAAP1LP21_15 All product labels should state ingredient and nutritional information.

name: qaap1lp21_16
label: QAAP1LP21_16 There should be no alcohol sponsorship of sports clubs, events or competitions.

name: qaap1lp_01
label: QAAP1LP_1 A minimum price of at least 50p per unit of alcohol, as already implemented in Scotland in 2018 and Wales in 2020, which is regularly reviewed.

name: qaap1lp_02
label: QAAP1LP_2 All products labels to feature large health warnings labels selected by an independent body.

name: qaap1lp_03
label: QAAP1LP_3 The sale of alcohol in shops should be restricted to specific times of the day and designated areas.

name: qaap1lp_04
label: QAAP1LP_4 The tax on an alcohol product should be in line with the product strength.

name: qaap1lp_05
label: QAAP1LP_5 Change licensing laws to reduce the availability of alcohol.

name: qaap1lp_06
label: QAAP1LP_6 Alcohol advertising and sponsorship should be restricted to newspapers - and other adult press - and limited to factual information.

name: qaap1lp_07
label: QAAP1LP_7 An independent body should be established to regulate alcohol promotion, including product and packaging design.

name: qaap1lp_08
label: QAAP1LP_8 The legal limit for blood alcohol concentration for drivers should be 50mg/100 ml. For context, it is 80mg/100 ml in England and Wales,

name: qaap1lp_09
label: QAAP1LP_9 All health and social care professionals should be trained to routinely provide brief alcohol advice to their clients.

name: qaap1lp_10
label: QAAP1LP_10 People who need support for alcohol problems should be routinely referred to specialist alcohol services.
